W. 13th Street, north side, west of Seventh Avenue,
(general view northward).

A photograph taken from a dwelling structure at the above location viewing up Seventh Avenue (at the right) and across W. 14th Street, to show tall structures built in the last several years, on and around Seventh Avenue. From left to right these are, the 19 story New York Telephone Co., Building (No. 206 W. 18th Street), the 18 story apartment house No. 90 Seventh Avenue (at the S.W. corner of W. 16th Street), the 18 story apartment house, No. 72 Seventh Avenue (S.W. corner of W. 15th Street) and the 18 story apartment house, No. 101 Seventh Avenue (N.E. corner of W. 16th Street across the latter appears the unfinished tower of the Empire State Building. To the left is the roof of the 7 story structure occupied by the publishing firm of Street and Smith (No. 79-89 Seventh Avenue).

February 6, 1931

P. L. Sperr

(1)
13th Street, west from and including Seventh Avenue, showing the clearing on the N.W. corner where the new Metropolitan Temple (Methodist Episcopal) is about to be erected. See earlier views of Seventh Avenue for the house which used to stand on this corner.

P. L. Sperr.

May 28, 1931.

(2)
A view mainly of the South side. Also shown are Nos. 40, 38 and 36 Seventh Ave., at, adjoining and south of the S.W. corner of 13th Street. The buildings are a portion of the famous Rhinelander Flats. The building bearing flag (208-218 West 13th Street, is P.S. No. 16). Also note the newly erected church at the N.W. corner.

(1)
West 13th Street, south side, west from Seventh to Eighth Aves., showing at the S.W. corner of Seventh Ave., an empty lot; the site of the former "Rhinelander Flats". Between this lot and P.S. No. 16 are two small houses (Nos. 204 and 206) which have similar small buildings at their rears. These structures are owned by the Hoguet estate and undoubtedly were erected shortly after the Rhinelander row. For further data see the New York Times, May 10, 1937 (illustrated) and the New York Sun of May 1, 1937.

July 19, 1937.

P. L. Sperr.

title: Manhattan: 13th Street (West) - 7th Avenue - [Rhinelander Row.]

text:
Seventh Avenue, at W. 13th Street (center) as viewed north eastward from the vacant lot on the west side of the Avenue between 12th and 13th Streets. Here stood the old row of buildings that were familiarly known as the "Rhinelander Flats" and which were recently demolished after several postponements. Note the P.A.L. (Police Athletic League) shack with checker players surrounding same which is staffed by W. P. A. employees. Buildings seen are on the east side of this thoroughfare; View No. 2 emphasizing the 13th to 14th Street block. To the left of this is the Metropolitan Temple at the N.W. corner of the Avenue and 13th Street. Opposite this and the S.W. corner of 14th Street is a large loft and office structure.

June 15, 1938.
Views 1 and 2

P. L. Sperr
